<subSubSection pageId="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[685,1173,991,1729]" pageId="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,814,1044,1065]" pageId="12">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is distinguishable from its congeners by the quadrate shape of the sixth antennomere.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="12.[685,1173,991,1729]" pageId="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,880,1124,1145]" pageId="12">Description. Size</emphasis>
: Length 7.0 mm; width 2.0 mm. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[685,742,1151,1172]" pageId="12">Form</emphasis>
: As in 
<figureCitation box="[819,904,1151,1172]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="22.[175,215,1444,1463]" captionTargetBox="[167,1157,203,1421]" captionTargetId="figure-120@22.[167,1157,192,1421]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Figs. 98–103. Pujoliclerus species, habitus. 98) P. ovatus; 99) P. wappesi; 100) P. amplus; 101) P. flavoapicalus;" pageId="12">Fig. 101</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[916,1033,1151,1172]" pageId="12">Integument</emphasis>
: Head mostly yellow, upper frons and epicranium with black; antenna mostly brown, last antennomere yellow; pronotal disc black, lower edges infuscated, remainder reddish yellow; elytra predominantly brown, epipleural margin slightly yellow posteriorly, apex yellow; legs mostly yellow, anterior margin infuscated; pterothorax and abdomen brown. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[767,823,1363,1384]" pageId="12">Head</emphasis>
: Eyes as wide as frons (16:16); funicular antennomeres considerably expanded, 6 
<superScript attach="left" box="[697,711,1411,1425]" fontSize="6" pageId="12">th</superScript>
antennomere quadrate and very large (
<figureCitation box="[1089,1161,1416,1437]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="8.[175,216,1487,1506]" captionTargetBox="[167,1170,207,1464]" captionTargetId="figure-1@8.[151,1172,183,1487]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs. 21–38. Pujoliclerus species, antennae. 21) P. helvinus; 22) P. maracayensis; 23) P. bilineatus; 24) P. calceatus; 25) P. corumba; 26) P. ovatus; 27) P. wappesi; 28) P. amplus; 29) P. flavoapicalus; 30) P. gilvus; 31) P. hermani; 32) P. alajuela; 33) P. orellana; 34) P. megacavus; 35) P. oxinus; 36) P. alboordinus; 37) P. apolegmus; 38) P. catarina." pageId="12">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[685,764,1443,1464]" pageId="12">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum transverse (47:42), lateral tubercle very prominent (
<figureCitation box="[935,1009,1469,1490]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="18.[175,215,1395,1414]" captionTargetBox="[151,1155,183,1382]" captionTargetId="figure-114@18.[151,1172,183,1383]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs. 48–61. Pujoliclerus species, pronota. 48) P. helvinus; 49) P. maracayensis; 50) P. modestus; 51) P. bilineatus; 52) P. calceatus; 53) P. corumba; 54) P. flavolimbatus; 55) P. ovatus; 56) P. wappesi; 57) P. amplus; 58) P. flavoapicalus; 59) P. gilvus; 60) P. hermani; 61) P. orellana." pageId="12">Fig. 58</figureCitation>
); epipleural fold gradually diminishing to elytral apex; asetiferous punctures prominent in anterior elytral half. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[685,784,1549,1570]" pageId="12">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Aedeagus not available.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[685,1173,991,1729]" pageId="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[709,886,1576,1597]" pageId="12">Natural History.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[956,1002,1576,1597]" pageId="12">type</typeStatus>
was collected during November.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
